    "updated_at": "2016-12-17T23:08:02Z",
    "body": "@MarshallOfSound A frameless window doesn’t differentiate between the content size and the size. So creating a window like this would get a viewport size of `500,500`, regardless of whether `useContentSize` is `true` or `false`:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nconst window = new electron.BrowserWindow({\r\n  width: 500,\r\n  height: 500,\r\n  frame: false,\r\n  useContentSize: // either `true` or `false`\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo if an offscreen window is the the same as a frameless window, this should give the same results:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nconst window = new electron.BrowserWindow({\r\n  width: 500,\r\n  height: 500,\r\n  useContentSize: // either `true` or `false`\r\n  webPreferences: {\r\n    offscreen: true\r\n  }\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\n…but it doesn’t. If `useContentSize` is true, you get `500,522` and `500,500` otherwise. That seems like a bug to me. Otherwise, if that oddity in the behavior is expected, it should at least be documented in the [offscreen guide](https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/master/docs/tutorial/offscreen-rendering.md)."
  },
